# ── Shadow (paper) crypto trader state ───────────────────────────────────────
# Mirrors the live quant strategy exactly — same 5 signals, same thresholds,
# same fee-aware Kelly — but simulates fills without touching Kalshi orders.
# ── Wave 3 Shadow Experiments (18 bots, A–R) ─────────────────────────────────
# Runs in parallel with the live trader whenever shadow_crypto_enabled=True.
# Matrix: 5 K-cluster + 5 L-cluster + 5 M-cluster + 3 O-cluster = 18 bots
#   K cluster (A-E): slot count axis — no coin cap, any edge, 10/15/20/25/30 slots
#   L cluster (F-J): protection axis — 30 slots, cap 0/10/15/20/25%
#   M cluster (K-O): edge threshold axis — 15 slots, 15% cap, 0/1/2/3/4¢ edge
#   O cluster (P-R): O-config edge axis — 20 slots, 15% cap, 0/1/2¢ edge
#
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# WHAT IS A "SHADOW BOT"?
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#   A shadow bot is a virtual trading bot that runs the EXACT SAME logic as
#   the live bot — same signals, same entry rules, same Kelly sizing — but
#   it NEVER actually places orders on Kalshi. It only tracks positions and
#   P&L in memory (Python dictionaries and integers).
#
#   Think of it like a flight simulator: same controls, same physics, but no
#   real plane in the air. The shadow bot lets us test different parameter
#   combinations in real market conditions (real prices, real timing) without
#   risking money.
#
#   When a market settles (resolves YES or NO), the shadow bot checks whether
#   its virtual position won or lost and adjusts its virtual balance accordingly.
#   Over time, we can compare: "Bot A with 60% threshold made +$X. Bot B with
#   65% threshold made +$Y. Bot C with 70% threshold made +$Z." The winner's
#   parameters get deployed to the live bot.
#
# WHAT IS A "WAVE"?
#   Each wave is a new generation of shadow bots testing different parameter
#   combinations. Wave 3 tests win-probability thresholds and edge requirements.
#   Wave 4 tests which MARKET TYPES to trade (15m only? or also daily?).
#   Wave 5 tests different Kelly sizing fractions with drawdown protection.
#   New waves are added as we learn from previous waves. It's an ongoing
#   A/B test of trading strategy parameters running in real-time.
#
# WHY 24+ BOTS SIMULTANEOUSLY?
#   Markets give us only a few hundred trades per week. Testing one parameter
#   set at a time would take months to get statistical significance.
#   By running many bots on the SAME market data simultaneously, we get the
#   equivalent of months of data in days. Bots A, B, C all see the same
#   BTC price signal at 3pm UTC — only their entry thresholds differ. This
#   is the most accurate way to isolate which parameter is causing the
#   performance difference.
#
# WHAT ARE THE KEY PARAMETERS?
#   win_prob (WP): minimum fair probability required to enter a trade.
#     WP60 = bot only bets when our model says ≥60% chance of winning.
#     WP65 = ≥65%, WP70 = ≥70%, etc.
#     Higher WP = fewer trades, each one higher confidence.
#
#   edge_cents (E): minimum price discount required to enter.
#     E0 = bet as long as WP is met, even at fair value.
#     E4 = fair_value must exceed market price by ≥4 cents.
#     E8 = at least 8 cents of discount (very selective).
#     Think of it as: "how cheap does this contract have to be vs what we
#     think it's really worth before we'll buy it?"
#
#   kelly_fraction (K): what fraction of "full Kelly" bet size to use.
#     K10 = 10% Kelly (very conservative, tiny bets)
#     K25 = 25% Kelly (quarter-Kelly, the default)
#     K50 = 50% Kelly (half-Kelly)
#     K100 = full Kelly (aggressive, maximizes log-growth but high drawdown)
#     The Kelly formula tells us the MATHEMATICALLY OPTIMAL bet size for a
#     given edge and win probability. Using a fraction of it provides a safety
#     buffer against model errors and estimation uncertainty.
#
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# THE KELLY FORMULA (f* = (p*b - q) / b)
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#   f* = fraction of bankroll to bet
#   p  = probability of winning (e.g., 0.65 = 65%)
#   q  = probability of losing = 1 - p = 0.35
#   b  = net odds received on a winning bet
#
#   In a Kalshi binary market priced at 55 cents:
#     If you buy YES at 55c, winning pays 100c (you profit 45c on a 55c bet)
#     So b = 45/55 ≈ 0.818 (you win 0.818x your stake if correct)
#
#   f* = (0.65 * 0.818 - 0.35) / 0.818
#      = (0.532 - 0.35) / 0.818
#      = 0.182 / 0.818
#      ≈ 22.2% of bankroll
#
#   With $333 balance, full Kelly = $74. Quarter-Kelly = $18.50.
#   In practice we clamp bets to the $2-$15 range for safety.
#
#   The Kelly formula MAXIMIZES long-run wealth growth. Betting MORE than
#   Kelly (or less but closer) leads to ruin eventually. Betting a FRACTION
#   of Kelly gives up some growth rate but dramatically reduces drawdowns.
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

_shadow_positions: dict[str, dict] = {}   # A: K1 — 10 slots, no cap, 0¢
# _shadow_positions is a dict keyed by Kalshi market ticker.
# Example: {"KXBTC15M-26MAR24-T65000": {"side": "yes", "entry_price": 62,
#           "count": 2, "fair_prob": 0.72, "entry_time": "2024-03-26T14:00:00Z"}}
# When the market settles, this entry is removed and the P&L is recorded in
# _shadow_trades.

_shadow_balance_cents: int = 8_000
# Virtual starting balance: $333.23 (33,323 cents). The underscore separators
# (_) are just for readability — same as writing 33323. The starting balance
# of $333.23 was chosen to mirror the live account size at the time of creation
# so shadow bot returns are directly comparable to live bot returns.

_shadow_trades: list[dict] = []
# Log of all completed shadow trades (entries that have settled or been stopped).
# Each dict has: time, action ("settled"/"stop_loss"), ticker, side, entry_price,
# exit_price, pnl_cents, won (bool). Used by /api/shadow to show trade history.

_SHADOW_MAX_TRADES: int = 500
# Maximum number of trades to keep in the shadow trade log before trimming.
# Prevents unbounded memory growth: after 500 settled trades, the oldest are
# dropped. The P&L metrics remain accurate because they're computed cumulatively.

_last_settlement_time: float = 0.0  # epoch time of last shadow settlement; 0 = never settled yet
# Used by the "freeze circuit breaker" (see below). If the bot has been running
# but no position has settled in 30+ minutes, something is wrong with Kalshi's
# settlement feed — the bot pauses new entries to protect capital.

# Capital-based position caps — limits by % of total capital locked, not position count.
# total_capital = locked_in_open_positions + remaining_cash
# This correctly scales: a 0.25 Kelly bot taking $2 bets can hold more positions than
# a 1.0 Kelly bot taking $15 bets, while both face the same capital exposure ceiling.
# Per-category caps guarantee each type always has remaining capacity even during a freeze.
#
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# WHAT IS THE CAPITAL CAP SYSTEM?
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#   Why not just limit to "max 10 open positions at once"?
#   Because position COUNT doesn't capture risk — a single $100 bet is riskier
#   than ten $2 bets. Capital caps measure by DOLLARS AT RISK, not count.
#
#   The nested cap structure works like this:
#
#   Level 1 — TOTAL cap (25%):
#     At any moment, at most 25% of the virtual balance can be locked in open
#     positions. If the bot has $333 and has already bet $84 (25%), it stops
#     opening new positions until some settle. This prevents a streak of bad
#     luck from wiping out the entire account before the losses can be observed.
#
#   Level 2 — CATEGORY caps (40%/10% of the locked budget):
#     Of the money that IS deployed:
#       - 15-minute binary markets can use at most 40% of the deployed budget
#         (so 40% × 25% = 10% of total balance in 15M markets)
#       - Daily/hourly "above/below" bracket markets can use at most 10%
#         (10% × 25% = 2.5% of balance in brackets)
#     This guarantees that if the bracket market model is wrong, it can only
#     lose 2.5% of the account — the 15M markets are the main engine.
#
#   Level 3 — PER-COIN cap (10% of deployed budget):
#     No single coin (e.g., BTC, ETH, XRP combined across all its markets)
#     can use more than 10% of the deployed budget. This forces diversification
#     across coins and prevents a single BTC crash from wiping out the portfolio.
#
#   Sub-caps are fractions of the LOCKED BUDGET, not of full balance.
#   This ensures the sub-caps "move with" the main allocation and don't
#   accidentally block all entries when the main cap is barely used.
#
#   Example at $333 balance:
#     _crypto_budget_cents = $333 × 0.25 = $83.25 max to deploy
#     Per-coin max = $83.25 × 0.10 = $8.33 in any single coin
#     15M max      = $83.25 × 0.40 = $33.30 in 15-minute markets
#     Bracket max  = $83.25 × 0.10 = $8.33 in directional daily brackets
#
# The _shadow_pos_type_ok() function (defined per-market-loop) implements
# this logic and returns True (allow entry) or False (cap reached, skip).
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
_SHADOW_CAP_LOCKED_TOTAL   = 0.30  # max 30% of capital locked — matches live bot 30% budget cap
_SHADOW_SLIPPAGE_CENTS: int = 2    # simulated entry slippage: live bot pays ~2c more than signal price
_SHADOW_CAP_LOCKED_15M     = 0.40  # max 40% locked in 15-minute binary (KXBTC15M, KXETH15M, ...)
_SHADOW_CAP_LOCKED_BRACKET = 0.10  # max 10% locked in above/below bracket — small allocation only
_SHADOW_CAP_LOCKED_PER_COIN = 0.20 # max 20% locked in any single coin — matches live bot 20% per-coin cap
_SHADOW_BRACKET_PFXS = ("KXBTCD","KXETHD","KXXRPD","KXSOLD","KXBNBD","KXHYPED","KXDOGED")
# _SHADOW_BRACKET_PFXS: these are the Kalshi series prefixes for "directional"
# markets — "Will BTC close ABOVE/BELOW $X by end of day?". These are longer-
# duration bets (1 hour to 1 week) vs the 15-minute binary markets.

_SHADOW_STALE_GRACE_SEC = 2700  # 45 min past close_time → write off position at entry cost
# What is a "stale position"?
#   Sometimes Kalshi's API is slow to publish settlement results — a market
#   might close at 3:15pm but the "settled: YES" result doesn't appear in the
#   feed until 3:20pm or later. During this gap, the shadow bot has positions
#   it can't settle because there's no result yet.
#   After 45 minutes past close_time with no settlement, we write off the
#   position at entry cost (P&L = 0) and free the capital. This prevents
#   a Kalshi API freeze from permanently locking the shadow bot's entire
#   virtual bankroll in limbo.

